Subject: EDID: advertise only the requested resolution (no ghost modes in games)

Apollo's generated EVDI EDID populated:
  - Established Timings byte: 0x21 0x08 0x00 → 640x480@60, 800x600@60, 1024x768@60
  - Standard Timings slots: 1920x1080@60, 1680x1050@60, 1600x900@60,
    1280x1024@60, 1280x720@60
plus the Detailed Timing Descriptor for the actually-requested mode.

Result: a virtual display created for a Steam Deck (1280x800@60) advertised
NINE resolutions to userspace. In any game's "Display" settings menu the
user saw a long list of phantom choices, even though only one of them
(the DTD) was supported by the apollo→client streaming pipeline.

User feedback after patch 0010 enabled the Resolution Scale Factor slider:
> "i dont like that it shows another resolutions below in the game display options"

Fix: zero out the established-timings bits and mark every standard-timing
slot as unused (0x01 0x01). The EDID now advertises ONLY the DTD —
exactly the resolution the apollo session was created with (possibly
scaled via the scale-factor slider). Games see a single resolution choice
and can't pick a mode the pipeline doesn't support.

The EDID checksum is recalculated downstream by calculate_edid_checksum(),
so the byte-level change is self-consistent.

For 4K extension cases (width > 1920 || height > 1080) there's a CEA-861
extension block that adds VICs (16=1080p60, 4=720p60, 95=4K60, etc.).
Those are out of scope for this patch — they only fire on >1080p clients
and the user is on a Steam Deck (≤1280x800). If the user starts streaming
at 4K and complains about VICs, we'll tighten that block too.

--- a/src/platform/linux/virtual_display.cpp
+++ b/src/platform/linux/virtual_display.cpp
@@ -811,19 +811,26 @@
     edid[29] = 0x4D; edid[30] = 0x9D; edid[31] = 0x25; edid[32] = 0x12;
     edid[33] = 0x50; edid[34] = 0x54;
 
-    // Established timings
-    edid[35] = 0x21; edid[36] = 0x08; edid[37] = 0x00;
+    // Established timings — cleared. The default upstream value
+    // (0x21 0x08 0x00) advertised 640x480@60, 800x600@60 and 1024x768@60
+    // which would surface in game display-settings menus as available
+    // resolutions even though the user only wants the one resolution the
+    // session was created with.
+    edid[35] = 0x00; edid[36] = 0x00; edid[37] = 0x00;
 
-    // Standard timings (8 entries, 2 bytes each)
-    // We'll add some common resolutions
-    edid[38] = 0xD1; edid[39] = 0xC0; // 1920x1080@60
-    edid[40] = 0xB3; edid[41] = 0x00; // 1680x1050@60
-    edid[42] = 0xA9; edid[43] = 0xC0; // 1600x900@60
-    edid[44] = 0x81; edid[45] = 0x80; // 1280x1024@60
-    edid[46] = 0x81; edid[47] = 0xC0; // 1280x720@60
-    edid[48] = 0x01; edid[49] = 0x01; // Unused
-    edid[50] = 0x01; edid[51] = 0x01; // Unused
-    edid[52] = 0x01; edid[53] = 0x01; // Unused
+    // Standard timings — all 8 slots marked unused (0x01 0x01) so games
+    // only see the DTD-advertised mode. Previously this block advertised
+    // 1920x1080, 1680x1050, 1600x900, 1280x1024, 1280x720, which would
+    // show up as alternate choices in any game's display menu — confusing
+    // for a virtual display sized exactly to the streaming client.
+    edid[38] = 0x01; edid[39] = 0x01;
+    edid[40] = 0x01; edid[41] = 0x01;
+    edid[42] = 0x01; edid[43] = 0x01;
+    edid[44] = 0x01; edid[45] = 0x01;
+    edid[46] = 0x01; edid[47] = 0x01;
+    edid[48] = 0x01; edid[49] = 0x01;
+    edid[50] = 0x01; edid[51] = 0x01;
+    edid[52] = 0x01; edid[53] = 0x01;
 
     // Detailed Timing Descriptor 1 (preferred timing)
     create_detailed_timing_descriptor(&edid[54], width, height, refresh_rate);
